# AGENTS.md — per-build agent contract for {{PROJECT_NAME}}

> Short, binding contract for any sub-agent spawned into this repo. Read `CLAUDE.md` first for the
> conventions; this file is the operating rules. If a rule here conflicts with a task prompt, this
> file wins — escalate the conflict, do not resolve it silently.

## Architecture pointer

- Conventions + the four append-only seams: `CLAUDE.md`.
- Contract layer invariants: `{{CONTRACTS_PKG}}/CLAUDE.md`.
- Module ownership (who owns which globs): `MODULES.md`.
- What "done" means: the acceptance-criteria ledger at `{{AC_LEDGER_PATH}}` — every AC is **verified**
  (a passing test for protected-core ACs, else live-app verification — see `CLAUDE.md` testing policy).

## Ownership & coordination

- You own **one module's globs** (see `MODULES.md`). Create and edit files only inside them.
- You may **append** to the four shared seams (schema dir, API registry, nav registry, contracts
  index) — one line each, never editing another module's line.
- The **{{CONTRACTS_PKG}} `package.json` version bump is the only cross-track coordination signal.**
  You do NOT bump it and you do NOT regenerate `openapi.yaml` / `api-types`. The integrator does
  that once at merge. If your work needs a new contract shape, add the Zod schema + the one index
  export line and STOP — flag it for the integrator.
- Consume shared-infra modules ({{SHARED_INFRA_MODULES}}); never fork them.

## Git discipline

- **Every sub-agent runs in an isolated git worktree.** The main tree is read-only to you.
- **Branch naming:** `{{TRACK}}/{{PHASE}}-{{TICKET_ID}}-s{{SESSION_SHORT}}`
  (e.g. `api/fix-w1-be-03-sA7B9`). The session-short suffix guarantees concurrent sessions can't
  collide; the ticket id makes `git log` readable.
- **Conventional commits**, scoped to your module. Cite the AC / requirement id in the body
  (`// {{REQ_ID_EXAMPLE}}`), never in user-facing strings.
- **Commit your own branch. NEVER push.** The orchestrator/integrator handles all merges.
- **Tag before you touch protected core.** Before any schema, migration, state-machine, RBAC, audit,
  or temporal/SLA change, the orchestrator tags a checkpoint. If you're about to touch one of these
  and no checkpoint exists, stop and escalate.
- **Forbidden, always:** `git push`, `--force` / `--force-with-lease`, `commit --no-verify`,
  `commit --amend`, `rebase` onto `origin/*`, any auto-merge, deleting tags, or editing history.
  History rewriting is the integrator's job only, on a fresh `*-atomic` branch.

## The merge gate (executable — run before you declare done)

Your branch must be **independently green**. Run the universal gate locally:

```bash
{{TYPECHECK_CMD}}      # must be clean
{{LINT_CMD}}           # must be clean
{{UNIT_TEST_CMD}}      # green (changed + adjacent modules)
{{CONTRACTS_BUILD_CMD}}# contracts build clean
{{E2E_CMD}}            # browser/e2e green (mocked early; real composed stack late)
```

The orchestrator re-runs these gates itself and **never trusts a self-declared "done."** Capture the
exact command output in your ticket's `## Resolution` block (commit SHA + gate result). A failure
that already existed at the baseline (see `BASELINE-NOTES`) is not your regression — say so
explicitly rather than papering over it.

## Autonomy rules

- **BRD/corpus silent?** Pick a **conservative default**, implement it, and log the decision in
  `docs/open-questions.md` with the requirement gap and your chosen default. Never guess statutory,
  financial, or rights-bearing behaviour — flag it instead.
- **Three gate failures on the same ticket?** Stop. File a blocker: move the ticket to
  `escalated/`, append `## Escalation reason` (what you tried, the failing output, your hypothesis).
  Do not thrash a fourth time.
- **Scope creep?** If the fix needs work outside your module's globs, do NOT reach across — file a
  new ticket for the other module's owner. Producers never edit their own queued tickets; mistakes
  become new tickets.
- **Out of your depth on protected core?** Escalate rather than improvise. A silent wrong transition
  or a missing audit row is worse than a blocked ticket.
